records.description: View of six military servicemen on the grass, around a campfire. Two of the men are crouching nearby the fire. Three of the men are eating, and two of the men are also holding glass beer bottles. One of the men is holding a cup. A wooden shed, or building, with shelves holding objects is in the background. There are cabbage trees. There is a wooden box, or crate, with "EVEREADY" written on it. A body of water, and bushes, are in the background.

creator: Hemus, Charles, 1849-1925
records.description:
Shows a group of Maori gathered informally around a camp fire on which they are cooking food. One man in a peaked cap and blue jacket squats in the centre watching the fire whose smoke drifts off to the left. Beside him is a kete possibly containing dry foliage to stoke the fire, and a bundle of blankets. At the left an old woman holds  a small plucked bird on a stick over the fire, while a child and a dog sit beside her. Behind the squatting man is a seated woman perhaps nursing a child, and a man carrying a child on his back. At the right is a group of three figures in Maori cloaks and European hatseft group is a raupo hut with two woven kete hanging from roof poles. The background shows a figure on a path leaing away up a small hill, with further hills in the distance. 
Backing board gave artist and title; photocopy kept with item. 
Other Titles - 19th century study of Maoris 
Inscriptions: Recto - bottom right - CTH 
Quantity: 1 watercolour(s). 
Physical Description: Watercolour, 250 x 345 mm.
records.title: Hemus, Charles, 1849-1925 :Kai time. [ca 1900]

records.description: Two surveyors and their dog warm themselves beside a campfire in this 1840s watercolour. Many 19th-century settlers brought animals with them, mainly to help with farm work. Dogs were essential for controlling sheep on unfenced runs. Over time, however, people came to treat many dogs as pets.
